HEADWORD: Saccharomyces
<hw>Sac`cha*ro*my"ces</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.,
fr. Gr. <?/ sugar + <?/, <?/, a fungus.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A
genus of budding fungi, the various species of which have the power, to
a greater or less extent, or splitting up sugar into alcohol and
carbonic acid. They are the active agents in producing fermentation of
wine, beer, etc. <spn>Saccharomyces cerevisiae</spn> is the yeast of
sedimentary beer. Also called <altname>Torula</altname>.</def><--
Brewers' yeast is Saccharomyces cerevisiae. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

